               <history>
                  <origin> Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but completed before <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1620" to="1621">1030 AH (1620–21 CE)</date>. </origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently owned by at least three owners, including an
                        unidentified owner who purchased the volume in <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1620" to="1621">1030 AH (1620–21
                           CE)</date> for 24 rupees, as well as the seal impressions of two other
                        men who either inspected or owned the volume named <persName
                           role="asn fmo seal" key="person_f7853">Luṭf Allāh</persName>, dated <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1617">1026 AH (1617 CE)</date> and
                           <persName role="asn fmo seal" key="person_f7854">Ṭālib Jāmī</persName>
                        dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1650" to="1651">1061 AH (1650–51
                           CE)</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580" key="person_66617580">Duncan Forbes
                           (1798–1868)</persName>, Professor of Oriental Languages at <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/128638237" key="128638237">King's
                           College</orgName>, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>In <date calendar="#gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>, he
                        published the volume in his library catalogue in which he offered it for £5,
                        5 shillings, but then later sold it to his publishers, <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/45159035185601380002"
                           key="person_45159035185601380002">W. H. Allen &amp; Co.</orgName> in
                        exchange for an annuity.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">Alexander
                           Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> later that same
                        year.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
